                     <interp inst="t18310630-267-person1920" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the son of 
               <persName id="t18310630-267-person1921">
                  Edward 
                  Richardson
               <interp inst="t18310630-267-person1921" type="surname" value="Richardson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310630-267-person1921" type="given" value="Edward"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310630-267-person1921" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , and am eleven years old; my father is a <rs id="t18310630-267-viclabel1392" type="occupation">jeweller</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310630-267-victim1919 t18310630-267-viclabel1392"></join>, and lives in Coram-street. On the 14th of May I was in Oxford-street, and saw the prisoner; I had seen him before in our street - he asked me where I had seen him last; I said at Russell-square, at the pump - he said he had been to the East Indies since that, and the mate of a ship had given him two poll parrots and two other birds - if I would go with him he would give me one of the parrots; I had some jewellery in my possession, which I took to Holles-street - he waited till I came out; he then spoke to me again, and we went to St. Martin's church steps; he then said I must give him my cap to put the parrot in, and my coat to wrap it in - I asked him if my waistcoat would not do, and he said No, it would fly out at the armholes; I took off my coat and cap, and gave them to him; he ran off - he out-ran me, and got away.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Which way did the person go after he had received your clothes? A. Towards the Strand.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310630-267-person1922">
